< Review>
That church rocked! The last time I went there was back N January 2009. Wish I was still attending, & still hearing the attendees cry out to the Most High! I also wish I lived Nx door to the house of the Lord. I miss it, & hopefully I will find a way to get back to that wonderful, glorious house of God! I became a member of Antioch back N May 2008, & I was real proud of it. My former Sister N Law found out by saying "Oh, I didn't know you joined Antioch, that's good". When I first attended it back N April 2008, i was given papers to fill out, & when the pastor told us to go around & say hello to everyone, the song " we're blessed N the city (we are blessed) was playing. My stepniece was baptized there. The band can really rock the hooouuussse! Wayne & Myesha Chaney R really awesome folks.
What I also miss, that @ the end of the service, while the pastor was speaking, his wife sang "choose life" N the background. The day before my 30th cake day, there was a saxophonist getting down performing the same tune! Because of that, I just want to revive those days.</Review>

The store is huge and quite popular depending on the days you come on. At any popular outlet store, you really have to know what you're looking for or at least an idea. This store has plenty of helpful associates that can help you what you're looking for, so get some help, start shopping, and get out!

Tip: Ask what's new? What's on sale? Best deal? Most popular items?

You can't control other shoppers, especially when they're foreigners...prepare to be annoyed with rude shoppers with no common courtesy. Luckily, the sales associates are plenty and friendly....happy shopping!<//Text>

Lacee Petrovsky</username>
< Review>
Whether you're a local looking to improve your diet or a visitor here for the "Fall Farm Experience", this is THE PLACE to be. I've seen  them pull carrots fresh from the ground and bring them straight to the stand. All fresh, all organic, delicious variety. My daughter loves coming here to pick tomatoes and flowers, or just enjoying the outdoors hunting for lizards and looking at frogs in the pond. The workers are all so down-to-earth too. You can tell they put care into their produce and community, never stopped providing for the public despite how challenging 2020 has been. The guy that owns 24 is very chill and the register gal is a total babe. Great farm, great people!! (Just remember this IS a real farm. Too many times I see people let their dogs or kids take off running through the produce, great place to take the family but please be respectful)</Review>

<UserId.>112592395420541152772< /UserId.><Text>Love, love, love 24Carrot farm!  Two of the friendliest people you will ever meet are Ben and Alison.  Very knowledgeable and always extra willing to answer questions or make recommendations about the produce at the farm.  The crew as a whole are hardworking and quick with smiles.  They‚Äôve also introduced us to other local offerings through their farm stand and online ordering.  If you haven‚Äôt done their you-pick flowers, you‚Äôve gotta try it.  Their flowers are well cared for and last way longer than grocery store flowers. They also offer you-pick strawberries and tomatoes (I think).  I haven‚Äôt done those yet, but the ones they carry in their farm stand are sooo on point with flavor!  I could go on and on with every interaction I‚Äôve had. < review>
The only real neighborhood bookstore left functional in Santa Cruz since Logos had closed down. Only place where you can get a Financial Times or Art Forum in Santa Cruz. Used and new books; massive children's section and even a foreign language section...Hosts author's events and many community events regularly. Sells local and a couple of national dailies, magazines and specialized journals; stationary, book related items, calendars, agenda and strangely, socks. Reader's club members get special discount s and store credit. Very personable and polite staffs.< /review>

<review>I've been seeing Dr. Switzer for years at the Perlman Clinic and love her! She will spend a whole hour with you if you need it; she never rushes you and gives the best hugs. She also looks you in the eye and listens, unlike other doctors I've seen in the past who seemed to be typing, checking their phone, and just preoccupied when I was talking.

She also diagnosed a weird condition I've had with my ear since I was a kid that no specialist has been able to make sense of...

Plus, Dr. Switzer doesn't just try to put your symptoms into a box; she diagnoses you based on not just tests, but also what she sees and what you tell her.

Lastly, no matter how bad you feel, she has one of those personalities that just makes you laugh.

If that doesn't convince you--I recently had to switch to Medi-Cal, and at the time they didn't take my plan (they do now!), but there was no way I was going to go see anyone other than Dr. Switzer, so I paid cash. She is worth it.

Oh yeah, and everyone in that office is super friendly and personable; they actually make an effort to remember your name!</review>< pictures>

<text>I went in for a rash. Brenna evaluated me and and said it was neither viral nor contagious and that it would resolve on its own. She recommended some over the counter itch creams and antihistamines. Two and a half weeks later, rash worsens and I see a dermatologist who diagnosed me with scabies, which is highly contagious. I ask Perlman clinic for a refund on the basis of a negligent misdiagnosis and am denied the refund on that grounds that Brenna's notes state to come back in one week if rash worsened, and it has now been two and a half weeks. I receive a copy of Brenna's notes which contained numerous false statements (the notes were not actively made available to me prior to this). The notes state that Brenna discussed with me a mental health issue which I do not have and that she prescribed me a free trial of medications for a condition which was never discussed, among other things. I do not think my request for a refund was taken seriously because their reasoning for denial is backed up by a flawed medical record.

Brenna and the front desk representatives conducted themselves in a very friendly and caring manner which I really appreciated but embellishing patients' medical records to make visitations seem more thorough than they were and not taking refund requests seriously are both unethical practices that I do not think are being addressed properly.</text>< gmap_id>

Our first time at The Bucket and we LOVED it. The place was recommended to us by a friend. Good atmosphere, family friendly, great service, wonderful yummy food! We ordered whole shrimp, fried shrimp n' chips, lobster tails, and a Dungeness crab. <rate>5<//rate>< Review>
Love this place! Came here for a date night since every kbbq was packed af. Plus I was craving crawfish lol. The prices here are reasonable so don't even trip. The customer service here is kinda lacking but it's not bad bad. We got of course crawfish, and my dad got a 1lb of king crab legs that he literally destroyed. He said it was good and that they tasted fresh. I agreed after I tried one, it's pretty darn good. As in for the crawfish I was kinda bummed they ran out of fresh crawfish but had frozen. So I decided for frozen anyways. We got all 3 flavors with hot spice, it was pretty enjoyable. Kinda wish they had more garlic but my tastebuds weren't super disappointed.</Review>

< user_id>
100834635085938538169< /user_id>
< Text>
Busy, but quick process. Get the coupon from the website and increase your refund! Make it easy and take the caps off your plastic as you use it instead of waiting until recycling day, and just put the caps in your residential "blue" recycler can at home, not the big deal everyone is making it out to be. No it's not clean, in case you haven't noticed, IT'S A RECYCLING CENTER. Some blame falls on the customer, the lot is littered with plastic caps, obviously the employees didn't put those there, just like much of our city, people don't seem to like to clean up after themselves. But there are brooms and dust pans available if you are so inclined to clean up your mess.
I purposely drive in from the south, because making a left in this town is such a hassle. Very large parking lot, with plenty of spaces. Went mid-day during the week, would assume weekends are much busier. Employees were quick to keep the line moving and to quickly replenish their stock of empty bins. We will always come back to recycle here.< /Text>

<Text>Reduce.  Reuse.  Recycle.

By no means am I a tree hugger, but I am a conservationist/environmentalist.  Recycling has been a part of my lifestyle since I was a wee laddie.  Hey, help nature & make a few bucks?  It's a win-win!

Bellflower Recycling Center (BRC) is my go-to recycling place when the plastic, aluminum & glass piles are taking too much space in the yard.  Coupons are sent out regularly via Valpak and other means, usually having the best pricing, with a price match guarantee on top of that.  A little grimy, a little dirty, BCE is a no-frills place with some fringe benefits for recyclers.

Here's how to separate your CRV recyclables-
Netted containers - plastic & aluminum
Wheeled trash containers & totes - color-sorted glass

Make sure to remove lids!

Service is not the most friendliest at BRC, but I haven't had any major issues.  Free coffee & donuts while they last are always a plus.  A reward shelf has various nifty gifties for those bringing in certain levels of cash amounts of recyclables.

Parking is via BRC's private lot & street parking.

Bellflower Recycling Center simply can't be beat when it comes to recycling redemption, granted you include the aforementioned coupon.  I usually avoid the morning rush, sticking to early afternoon in order to maximize my time.  C'mon, if you don't recycle, then you're literally throwing money away!  Why not stuff your wallet with some cool cash money by recycling at BRC?  At the very least, you'll have money for food, and that's nothing to sneeze at.  Not at all!

Highly recommend!<//Text><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Response>
None< /Response>

<userid>114284853719842834579< /userid><name>Aimee Hager<//name><Date>1620582869443</Date>< rate>
5</rate>
< text>
What a great place and it gave us a shed of normalcy again. My husband and I were looking for a place with music, outdoor dining and drinks. My friend recommended Cornerstone. I called ahead to get an idea of the vibe and spoke to a gentleman named Mendoza. He told us he would take care of us and he did. We showed up right before the time we were told it would get crowded. We had a table outside near the fire pits, in ear shot of the DJ. It was awesome. The food was great, drinks were yummy and strong ( for me but I'm a cheap date My husband said they were perfect). Delicious German beer that my husband loved.
Staff came around often to check on guests. As the night went on the crowds got bigger. All wearing masks. I'm glad we stayed outside, inside was a bit too crowded for me as the night went on. But it made me happy to see people dancing inside. I was worried this was another club like atmosphere full of 20-30somethings and we would look out of place, but not at all. People of all ages were present ( we are in our 40's). The DJ played music from 90's Era to present..
Bar tenders were attentive. It was all around great business. Can't wait to go back. We were told live music will begin again soon. Thanks to Mendoza and the entire staff for giving my husband and I the first real date night we have had since the Pandemic started.</text>

<text>Cavernous & spacious. Almost to the high-end for flavor & technique on the Manhattan that was ordered. Only one bartender when we went so if it's busy, it'll take a good few minutes. < review>
I've been to bar/restaurant portion many times and enjoy their food. It does get busy so keep an eye on the person helping your table. However, Justin is great and quite exceptional.  Last night was my first time going to see music in the back on a busy Saturday. If seeing show, I highly suggest going when the music venue doors open and going upstairs to the balcony to get a bar stools. Also, there are great views of the stage up there.  Otherwise, its just an open floor plan for standing on the ground floor. There a few chairs against the wall on the ground floor too. If you are seeing the show,  get your drinks at the bar inside the music venue. There are less people and you need a plastic cup once inside the music venue anyway. We didn't know that and waited forever at the main bar. Before we could go into the music venue we had to wait to transfer our drinks to a plastic cup, right there at the door. It was awkward. But all in all, a fabulous venue for music, food, drinks and fun.</review>

Great place to play music. Good beers great staff<//text>
< GmapID>

</record></dataset><record>
< text>
The few shows I've seen at this venue haven't filled to capacity, which is a bit awkward, but it's not for lack of trying. The sound system is great, the music hall is clean, the beer selection is fantastic, and the bands they bring through are solid. Cornerstone's been a huge shot in the arm for Bay Area emo and pop punk, which previously was limited to essentially Bottom of the Hill and Slim's.

I'll keep seeing shows here as long as they keep booking them, and I hope word gets out that Cornerstone is worth the trip from SF. Berkeley is a bit isolated from the rest of that concert scene and late-night BART to the area is a pain but it's easily one of the best venues in the region.</text>

<Review>I'll reserve the fifth star until I've had a chance to eat more food there and visit a few times. For now I will say this is a spacious, light and airy conversion of the previous dark pool hall into beer and food venue with attached music space. There's even an outdoor patio with fire pits.

Went here with a group of a about a dozen folks and we were able to reserve a couple of long communal tables. On a Tuesday night it was plenty quiet enough for conversation among us which is a pleasant change from bars that insist on making you shout. They had a good selection of craft beers and a full bar for the non-beer drinkers.

Food that I tasted was good and a nice variety of smaller plates often being a twist on more traditional pub fare. For instance I had pork belly nachos - very tasty and good to share.

There are some larger seating areas a big group could congregate although not as convenient if you wanted to eat anything that want finger food. The outdoor area does not have heat lamps so in the winter (which is most of summer here too) you will need to dress warm or huddle close to the fire.< /Review>< pics>
None</pics>

< Text>
I have fibromyalgia, osteoarthritis, and plantars faciitis.  When I fell against the the table, a security guard was right there to escort me out, saying he had "multiple complaints", which was a lie! No one I had been in contact with had complained about me; not one. When my ankle turned, as oft times it does, and I fell against their wobbly table, which had been a problem all night, as none their tables are, security was right there, a minute later, to accuse me of being drunk and insisted on escorting me out, making me feel like the bad guy. If people were educated about invisible disabilities, this would never have happened.
If the security guard had smelled anyone elses breath, he would have smelled the same.
Instead, he treated me like a drunk, deciding my disabilities were a lie. I DID NOT LIE! He never offered me ice for my ankle, until I asked. I should have asked for the manager.

The notice with the ticket said to let the venue know if you had a condition that needed seating; however, there was NO ONE to speak with. My husband and I were lucky to find a table to sit at, for when I couldn't stand.

Because of CORNESTONE's lack of understanding and lack of care for it's customer's conditions, I missed the end of a concert I had been looking forward to for more than a decade.<//Text>

< text>
This place was very nice and open, with a wooden top bar vs a metal top bar with spaced barstools. The host was friendly and greeted us promptly and offered us menus. We chose to sit at the bar and the bartender greeted us quickly and gave us food menus. She made our drinks while we waited for our food. She was incredibly nice and patient with my friends dairy allergy. The music was loud enough to hear but subtle enough to talk which was great. Our bill was pretty low even though she waved a drink off for using rum instead of tequila, which we didn't mind. The only reason I put 4 instead of 5 is because the food portion was a bit small. Normally we get anything and share fries and be stuffed but we ended up eating somewhere else after too. This place has big tables for larger groups and a wide selection of beer on tap and alcohol. I definitely recommend this place.<//text>

< user>
113878473452384092613<//user>
<username>N B<//username><time>1559351800833</time><rating>5</rating><Text>Overall: excellent food, drink selection, and service! Ordered a salad, charcuterie board, and sausage... boy did they deliver! Very generous portion sizes, and all very delicious. The grilled bread is a great side, pairs well with everything and has enough flavor and texture to stand on its own. The condiments that come with the sausages and board were varied and fantastic, added a lot of fun to the meal.

They offer 3 tasters per person for drinks of which my party agreed that SLO Brew Cali-Squeeze (Blood Orange Hefeweizen), Moonlight Black to Reality (Czech Dark Lager... very dark!), and Mission Trail Aqua Dulce (cider... not too sweet) were the favorites.

Our server was very very kind and accommodating even though he was just about to clock out. He made really great, descriptive suggestions and was very knowledgeable on what they had available. Made sure we had all the tasters, drinks, and food we needed before seeing us off for the night. Could not ask for more considerate and cheerful service.

One note is that this place can be very popular with students so we had our IDs checked and partway through the night we were informed that a party of college students was coming in so we had to put on wristbands to order more drinks past a certain time. It was no hassle and the employees were efficient in notifying us and getting wristbands for us. There are restrooms available with multiple stalls which was great especially after the group event had started.

Photographed: Superfood Salad, Build Your Own Board with prosciutto/Barely Buzzed cheddar/aged Spanish manchego, Bavarian Bratwurst Sausage<//Text>< pics>
None< /pics>

< Review>
The food is gross. The chef is apparently not receptive when it comes to constructive criticism (to him, "simple" food means "lacking in flavor and generally unpalatable"). I visited to try the food twice: once when they first opened the kitchen (which is when you would expect them to put their best foot forward), then again recently, because I wanted to give them the benefit of the doubt.

The music venue is cool. The recreational activities are fun. The liquor selection is nothing to write home about.

The owner is only passionate about filling his pockets and getting chummy with college girls in the VIP section during shows. But hey, what do you expect from that super classy old guy who runs Pappy's?

There are too many good places in Berkeley to waste one's time helping this slob line his pockets.< /Review>

<rate>3< /rate><Review>Went to this place for the music venue, so I'll be reviewing it as such and not as a brewhouse.

The stage is pretty small but the floor is pretty huge. One thing's for sure, the emergency exits are so visible that it can be distracting when viewing from the second floor. But then again, that might just be me.

House speaker sounds ain't that great but again, it might just be the fault of the sound engineer. It was however obvious that even the bands were having a hard time hearing themselves despite the looooong soundcheck by their tech crew.

Lights were cool and overall aesthetic is pretty nice. Connected to the music venue is the brewhouse, so having craft beer in a music venue is definitely a plus. They have food as well, if you're hungry. Their food is topnotch. <userid>107095315350388129588< /userid>< name>
Chris Iverson<//name>
< Date>
1492201183784</Date>
< rating>
1</rating>
< Review>
The bar itself was very pleasant and friendly. However the staff for the music venue need to seriously rework their policies. I went to the Offspring show last night and was ejected for crowdsurfing onto the stage, along with several others who did the same thing. When I tried talking to a few of the staff at the door, they told me I was "done" and needed to leave.

Firstly, it's a punk show; crowdsurfing is going to happen whether you like it or not. If you don't want people reaching the stage, then put a barricade up. Second, if people do get onstage and you don't want them there, SAY SOMETHING. Give warnings and escort people back to the floor. Resorting immediately to ejection without willing to discuss what happened is ridiculous and unprofessional.

There was also an incident where I was thrown out (attention to the word "thrown") after falling on somebody and not being able to get back up, but that was more confusing than anything and less of a problem since I was able to blend with a group re-entering with no trouble. But still, that could be a lawsuit waiting to happen if someone seriously injures themselves being man-handled like that.

Those tickets were not cheap, and having my night almost ended over something as trivial as crowdsurfing is absurd. I would have been willing to tone my actions down if I knew it was prohibited, but there was nothing that indicated it was, and no one was willing to talk to me about it after it happened. If this is how the staff at the venue are always going to be then I will take my business elsewhere.< /Review>
